################################################################################
Instructions for installing the SALT FP pipeline in its current form:
################################################################################

-Make sure the gfortran package is installed, then execute the
following commands in the download directory:
> make
> make clean

-This will create the file "voigtfit.so" which must be in the directory where
you're running the pipeline code.

-Make sure you have the following python packages installed:
numpy
scipy
matplotlib
astropy
photutils
pyraf
zsalt

-Many of these are available via "pip install <packagename>" To install zsalt,
go to https://github.com/crawfordsm/zSALT

-Make sure you have IRAF, Pyraf, and PySALT installed.

-Run the following python command in the download directory:
python setup.py install

-You may need to run this command as root if your python path is root-protected

-Now the SALT FP pipeline ought to be installed in your python path.

################################################################################
Instructions for running the pipeline in its current form:
################################################################################

-Make sure the file "voigtfit.so" is in the file you plan to operate in.

-Open a python terminal (ipython or python), then executethe following:
>>> import saltfppipe.pipeline
>>> saltfppipe.pipeline.pipeline(rawdir = "<path_to_raw_directory>")
Where here <path_to_raw_directory> is the directory containing raw FP image
data from SALT.

-Alternatively, you may ignore this keyword argument if you are operating in the

directory directly above "raw/". I.e. if "ls" reveals the "raw/" directory, this
argument can be ignored.

-You may also call the pipeline from command line by using:
> python <path_to_pipeline_directory>/pipeline.py <path_to_raw_directory>

-Once again, the last argument can be ignored if you are in the directory
directly above "raw/".
